<item>
            <title>[SPR-13588] Skip Content-Disposition header when status != 2xx</title>
                <link>https://jira.spring.io/browse/SPR-13588</link>
                <project id="10000" key="SPR">Spring Framework</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;The fix to protect against RFD exploits (&lt;a href=&quot;https://jira.spring.io/browse/SPR-13548&quot; title=&quot;Protect against RFD exploits&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;SPR-13548&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;SPR-13548&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt;) introduced a &lt;tt&gt;&quot;Content-Disposition:attachment;filename=f.txt&quot;&lt;/tt&gt; response header for &lt;tt&gt;@ResponseBody&lt;/tt&gt; methods where the URL appears to have an extension that is neither whitelisted by default nor explicitly registered by the application.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The URL checked for extensions is always the original URL even in the case of a forwarded request. In the case of an ERROR dispatch, Servlet containers are expected to set up the same request attributes as for forwarded requests. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Since Spring Boot relies on ERROR dispatches, a request with an unknown extension that results in an error can be rendered with a Content-Disposition header. This doesn&apos;t appear to cause issues in the browser but we should explore whether we can drop the header in such cases.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Note this issue was originally reported under &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-boot/issues/4220#issuecomment-148917466&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;Spring Boot ticket #4220&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

</description>
